6.
 Policy Statement
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.1 Operational Authority and Autonomy
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
The Information Operations Department shall maintain 
\series bold
comprehensive operational authority
\series default
 over the administration,
 security,
 architecture,
 and configuration of all Elko County information systems,
 infrastructure,
 and technology assets placed under the governance of the Information Operations Department as defined in 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:1.06"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Unified Authority
\series default
:
 To support compliance with the strict connectivity and security requirements of the 
\series bold
FBI CJIS Security Policy Section 5.1.1.4
\series default
,
 Elko County has adopted a unified governance structure for shared infrastructure.
 Under this structure,
 the IT Director retains final decision-making authority over all technical controls and risk mitigation strategies across the enterprise,
 subject to the statutory management control authority of Criminal Justice Agencies (CJA) over CJIS data policy.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Independence
\series default
:
 While administratively reporting to County Management,
 the Department's operational decisions shall be driven by technical standards,
 security mandates,
 and risk assessments.
 Political pressure or external influence shall not supersede mandatory security controls or engineering standards.
 Technical decisions shall be made in accordance with the delegation framework defined in 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:1.08"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.2 Chain of Command and Escalation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
The chain of command is a mechanism for accountability and risk management.
 Personnel shall utilize the chain of command to ensure decisions are made at the appropriate authority level.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Act Decisively
\series default
:
 Personnel shall execute duties with precision within their assigned scope of authority.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Escalate with Purpose
\series default
:
 Personnel shall escalate issues to their direct supervisor 
\series bold
within the same business day
\series default
 when operational risk,
 legal constraints,
 or policy ambiguity exceed their defined authority or expertise.
 During active incidents,
 escalation shall occur as soon as safely possible without interrupting critical response activities.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Unified Direction
\series default
:
 Leadership is defined by judgment,
 communication,
 and accountability,
 not solely by title.
 Once a decision is made by the designated authority,
 personnel shall implement that decision promptly.
 Concerns about implementation shall be raised through the escalation process defined in 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:1.08"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
 without impeding execution unless a safety or legal issue is identified.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.3 Leadership and Crisis Management
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
Leadership in Information Operations is defined by consistency,
 clarity,
 and accountability.
 Supervisors and designated leads shall:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Communicate with Precision
\series default
:
 Ambiguity causes downtime.
 Instructions and status reports shall be clear,
 specific,
 and actionable.
 Personnel shall confirm understanding of critical directives before execution.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Decide based on Standards
\series default
:
 Operational decisions shall be based on data,
 policy,
 and formal risk assessment,
 not sentiment or pressure.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Accountability
\series default
:
 Shall acknowledge errors transparently and document lessons learned within 
\series bold
five (5) business days
\series default
 of incident closure.
 Remediation actions shall be tracked to completion in the designated system of record.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Crisis Discipline
\series default
:
 During major incidents,
 personnel shall adhere to established Incident Response protocols (
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:4.01"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
).
 Leaders shall provide clear,
 evidence-based direction to maintain operational discipline and prevent panic-driven decision-making.
 Leaders shall participate in formal post-incident reviews to document lessons learned.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.4 Operational Discipline
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
Operational discipline is the foundation of the Department's credibility.
 Personnel shall execute duties according to the following standards:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Own the Scope
\series default
:
 Personnel shall fully own tasks within their job role.
 If a task falls outside their scope,
 they shall escalate it with clear context and documentation rather than ignoring it.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Document as Standard
\series default
:
 Dependence on memory or hallway conversations is prohibited in accordance with 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:5.01"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
.
 All operational actions,
 changes,
 and decisions shall be documented in the designated System of Engagement (Redmine) within 
\series bold
24 hours of completion
\series default
,
 except during active incident response where documentation shall occur during incident closure in accordance with 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:4.01"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
.
 Documentation shall be maintained in systems designated as records repositories in accordance with 
\series bold
NRS 239
\series default
.
 Required documentation shall be completed.
 Failure to document required actions constitutes noncompliance and may result in corrective action under 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:5.01"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Prioritize based on Risk
\series default
:
 Urgency shall be assessed based on impact to County operations and security,
 not solely on the volume of the request.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Resolve or Escalate
\series default
:
 Issues shall not remain in a stagnant state.
 Every ticket or work order must be actively moved toward resolution or escalated to the appropriate tier with sufficient context for action.
\end_layout

